# Privacy and Security Rules

These rules apply to every code change without exception.

## Default Privacy Contract

- All user content stays local. No network calls for content processing unless the user explicitly enables a remote provider.
- No content telemetry, no hidden analytics, no background uploads.
- No remote model calls without explicit user opt-in.
- Storage locations must be explicit, documented, and easy for the user to inspect, export, and delete.

## Never Do These Things

- Send imported text to an API without clear opt-in.
- Log raw sensitive content remotely.
- Enable cloud sync without explicit configuration.
- Transmit embeddings or content off-device without disclosure.
- Silently switch from local to remote processing.
- Hide network usage in background flows.

## Provider Separation

If adding model-dependent behavior, it must go through a provider interface:

```typescript
interface EmbeddingProvider {
  readonly isLocal: boolean;
  embed(text: string): Promise<number[]>;
}
```

Local and remote implementations must be clearly separated. The UI must disclose when a remote provider is active and what data is being sent.

## Privacy Claims

Only make claims that are technically true. Prefer: "By default, your data stays on your device." Avoid: "Nothing can ever leak."
